ce:section.ce:para:
Solvothermal/hydrothermal treatment is the most widely used method to prepare nanomaterials [54,67,68]. The as-obtained QDs by this method have the advantages of easy treatment, high quantum yield, uniform size, and environment friendliness [69–71]. Moreover, the method is easy to achieve the surface modification and functionalization of QDs synchronously, which will further improve the yield and efficiency and realize multifield applications of QDs [54,64,68,72–75]. For example, Teo's group first dispersed the bulk h-BN in DMF solvent by ultrasonication treatment for 8 h, and then the as-obtained suspension was centrifuged at 1500 rmp for 10 min to remove the large particles and obtain highly dispersed nanosheets [54]. Subsequently, the as-obtained nanosheets were placed in a Teflon-lined autoclave and subjected to a solvothermal treatment at 200 °C for 24 h [54]. When the solvothermal treatment terminated, the high-quality BNQDs can be obtained after high-speed centrifugation and filtration (Fig. 6
                           ) [54]. This liquid exfoliation-solvothermal treatment method allows a yield of 19.5% to be achieved [54]. Meanwhile, the authors also investigated the effects of filling factor (40 and 66.7%), synthesis temperature (120, 160, and 200 °C), and duration time (12, 24, and 36 h) on the morphology and optical properties of BNQDs [54]. The TEM and AFM images (Fig. 7
                           ) show that when the suspension filling factor in the hydrothermal autoclave was 66.7%, the synthesis temperature was 200 °C and the duration time was 24 h, the as-obtained BNQDs show a minimum lateral size of 2.62 nm and an average thickness of about three atomic layers [54]. In addition, the photoluminescence spectra show that the emission peak of the large-size BNQDs prepared at 6 h has a slight blue shift comparing with that of smaller BNQDs prepared at 36 h [54]. This slight blue shift may be due to the differences in the average lateral size, edge, and surface of the BNQDs prepared at different duration [54]. Clearly, this method is a simple and efficient way to obtain BNQDs with controllable particle size and high quantum yield. Meanwhile, it can be found through the above studies that the solvothermal treatment technology for the preparation of BNQDs has been relatively comprehensive and mature. In the following studies, researchers should consider modifying BNQDs to further optimize their performance.
